main event: On October 11, 1958, a radar at the Laredo Test Site in Laredo, Texas observed an unidentified target which was likely a meteor or two meteors occurring at nearly the same time.
interesting points: The radar observation lasted for about 28 seconds, with data showing characteristics that could be attributed to a meteor or meteors.
The observation indicated that the object suddenly appeared in three beams, with distinct sections showing range changes and relative accuracy.
The document suggests possible sources of the observed target, including a rocket launched from the White Sands Proving Ground, a passing satellite, a meteor, or unknown and unexpected objects.

There was a recommendation to verify with the White Sands Proving Ground for any firings on the date of the observation and to check with the Harvard College Observatory for possible meteor observations.
The report does not contain any information which would indicate the presence of any unconventional aircraft.
result: prosaic explanation: likely a meteor or two occurring at the same time
witnesses: Military personnel operating the radar at the Laredo Test Site
photographs: no photographs were included in the report
